  <h1 class="phase-title"><span>Phase 1</span></h1>
  <section class="card content-block">
    <h2>Problem</h2>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Xpress Weigh&rsquo; is a legacy suite of tools used by Consultants
      to run weekly member groups. The software runs on Windows tablets and
      supports enrolment, payments, weight recording, and access to member data
      during live sessions.

      <p>
        Accumulated technical and design debt left the system difficult to use
        and maintain, and misaligned with the goals of group delivery. As
        Slimming World began exploring wider digital transformation, the member
        support experience came under particular scrutiny. Complex, cluttered
        screens were acting as a barrier to the essential human connection that
        is at the heart of the group.
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>
          I was tasked with delivering targeted, interim usability improvements,
          with a specific focus on reducing friction and protecting the human
          connection that underpins a successful group experience.
        </strong>
      </p>
    </p>
  </section>
  <div class="image-row image-row--full image-row--2">
    <img src="/images/xpress-weigh/orig1.png" alt="Existing screen designs" />
    <img src="/images/xpress-weigh/orig2.png" alt="Existing screen designs" />
  </div>
  <p class="image-row--caption">
    <em>Exisiting solution: </em>Two complex screens were a barrier to natural,
    supportive member conversations.
  </p>
  <section class="card content-block">
    <h2>Approach</h2>
    <p>
      Years of embedded <strong>ethnographic exposure</strong> ‚Äî participating in
      groups as both a member and assistant ‚Äî provided a grounded understanding of
      real-world use. Targeted <strong>one-to-one research interviews</strong> with
      Consultants across experience levels validated and sharpened those insights.
    </p>

    <p>
      The findings were consistent: live sessions were slowed by <strong
        >hunt-and-peck navigation</strong
      >, most available data went untouched, and <strong
        >workarounds had become normalised</strong
      >. The problem wasn‚Äôt capability ‚Äî it was <strong
        >excess and friction</strong
      > in a high-tempo environment.
    </p>

    <p>
      In <strong
        >close collaboration with the Directors of Field and Training</strong
      >, I reframed the tool around <strong
        >essential actions and essential data</strong
      >. We removed peripheral information, reduced cognitive load, and designed
      for <strong>standing, in-group use</strong>.
    </p>

    <p>
      The outcome was a streamlined interface built around <strong
        >single-click input</strong
      > and <strong>faster information retrieval</strong> ‚Äî a system that supports
      Consultants in the moment, rather than competing for their attention.
    </p>
  </section>
  <div class="image-row image-row--full">
    <img src="/images/xpress-weigh/311-2.png" alt="Updated screen designs" />
  </div>
  <div class="image-row--caption">
    <ul>
      <li>
        The resulting design is cleaner and more accessible while remaining
        consistent with the wider application.
      </li>
      <li>
        Key data points are prioritised visually and optimised for quick
        glancing.
      </li>
      <li>Data entry happens in context rather than in a separate screen.</li>
      <li>
        Previous/next navigation spans almost the full height of the screen,
        designed around the ergonomics of holding and operating a tablet while
        standing.
      </li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <section class="card content-block">
    <h2>Impact</h2>
    <p>
      I rapidly produced, usability tested, and iterated ‚Äî removing the risk of
      costly changes during development.
    </p>

    <p>
      Released as an optional setting (&lsquo;classic&rsquo; or
      &lsquo;new&rsquo;), the redesign saw &gt;90% uptake within the first six
      weeks ‚Äî despite a typically change-resistant audience.
    </p>
    <p>
      Site visit data confirmed a clear uplift in Quality of Service following
      implementation
    </p>
  </section>

  <h1 class="phase-title">
    <span>Phase 2</span>
  </h1>

  <section class="card content-block">
    <h2>Building on success</h2>
    <p>
      As Slimming World embarked on a full digital transformation, I was tasked
      with leading the redesign of the full suite of tools used to support the
      Consulatnts across all aspects of running their business.
    </p>
  </section>
  <div>
    <img src="/images/xpress-weigh/ecosystem.png" />
  </div>
  <p class="image-row--caption">
    My Consultant ecosystem map indicates the scale and scope of my role in the
    business' digital transformation. <br />The red circle highlights the
    subject of this article.
  </p>
  <section class="card content-block">
    <h2>Problem</h2>
    <p>
      The member-support screens came back into focus at executive level, with
      broader stakeholder involvement and a strong appetite for transformation.
    </p>

    <h3 style="text-align:center; margin:var(--space-8) 0;">
      ‚ÄúWe‚Äôre not changing the group process.‚Äù
    </h3>
    <p>
      While there was a transformational mindset around the technology, group
      procedure was considered sacrosanct. The platform could change; the live
      group experience could not.
    </p>

    <p>
      An early part of my role was making this distinction clear: the technology
      was subservient to the group process. Its job was to support a 50-year-old
      operating model ‚Äî not compete with or redefine it.
    </p>
  </section>
  <section class="image-row image-row--full-bleed">
    <p class="image-overlay">Tap to view full map</p>
    <button
      class="lightbox-trigger"
      type="button"
      data-lightbox-target="journey-map"
