  <p class="image-row--caption">
    I mapped two years of the Consultant lifecycle as an anchor for the wider
    ecosystem redevelopment. This served multiple projects and products, and was
    helpfed to bring clarity to what belonged in group and what happened
    outside.
  </p>
  <section class="card content-block">
    <h2>Approach</h2>

    <p>
      The user journey map created a shared view of the end-to-end process and
      became a reference point in conversations about what data truly belonged
      on screen. For example, extensive historical data, while valuable for
      context, was repositioned into preparation and reporting workflows.
    </p>

    <p>
      Working directly with the board and senior stakeholders, I defined the
      tool in detail ‚Äî down to what appeared on screen and how it needed to
      perform under real-time pressure. Through workshops, co-design sessions
      and a <a
        href="https://www.uxforthemasses.com/buy-the-feature/"
        target="_blank"
        rel="noopener">buy-your-data prioritisation exercise</a
      > with senior consultants and the company owner, we clarified what stayed visible,
      what got cut, and made explicit trade-offs to ensure each data point earned
      its place.
    </p>

    <p>
      I also organised service safaris with product and engineering colleagues
      to build shared understanding of the live group environment. A Six
      Thinking Hats session tested the approach against operational and
      technical realities, refining it for practical use.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="callout--full-bleed full-bleed--text">
    <blockquote>
